Actually, if they can get the data back (be it because it's stored in plaintext or in obfuscated plaintext) then it's not secure. Obfuscation doesn't make it more secure, or any less plaintext.
On Wed, Apr 6, 2011 at 11:01 AM, Romain Bourdy <achileos@...il.com<mailto:achileos@...il.com>> wrote:
Hi Full-Disclosure,

Just my two cents but ... the fact they can give your password back doesn't mean it's stored in cleartext, just that it's not hashed but encrypted with some way to get the original data back, this doesn't mean at all it's not secured, even though in most case it's not.

 -Romain

